Practical 4: Repository Creation & Version Control using Git
Aim
To create and manage a GitHub repository using basic Git commands.
Requirements
• Git installed on system
• GitHub account
• Internet connection

Step 1: Login to GitHub
1. Open browser.
2. Go to https://github.com
3. Login to your GitHub account.

Step 2: Create a New Repository
1. Click on "New Repository".
2. Enter repository name (example: git-practical4).
3. Select Public.
4. Click Create Repository.

Step 3: Open Git Bash and Create Project Folder
Commands:
cd Desktop
mkdir Git_practical_1
cd Git_practical_1

Step 4: Initialize Git Repository
Command:
git init

Step 5: Create Sample Files
Commands:
echo "Hello Git" > file1.txt
echo "Git Practical" > file2.txt
echo "Version Control" > file3.txt

Step 6: Check Git Status
Command:
git status

Step 7: Add Files to Staging Area
Command:
git add .

Step 8: Commit Files
Command:
git commit -m "Initial project commit"

Step 9: Connect Local Repository to GitHub
Command:
git remote add origin https://github.com/username/git-practical4.git

Step 10: Verify Remote Repository
Command:
git remote -v

Step 11: Push Files to GitHub
Command:
git push -u origin main
Result
The GitHub repository is successfully created and the project files are pushed using Git commands.
